$ trace-cmd -p wakeup_rt

This tracer only saves the highest latency recorded at the system level by any RT priority task. This trace shows the record of the worst scheduling latency captured during execution (in this case, a delay of 230 µs).

Analyzing the log, we notice that the recorded event is not related to the cyclictest thread, but concerns the wakeup of a kernel process dedicated to managing the communication interface: irq/32-imx_mu_c (PID 122).

Since cyclictest wakes up "only" every 2 seconds, it experiences latencies below this threshold. Consequently, its wakeups never suffer a delay higher than the maximum already recorded in the system, and the tracer discards its logs, leaving only the worst record visible.

    The first stack trace is a snapshot taken (by the probe_wakeup function) at the moment of wakeup, showing the state of the waker.

    The second stack trace is a snapshot taken (by the probe_wakeup_sched_switch function) during the context switch, which almost certainly occurs within the __schedule function. 
    it provides the state of the process that executed __schedule. This could be the waker itself, if it reached __schedule directly within the same call chain as the wakeup, or a different process that was interrupted by an IRQ. 
    The handler for that interrupt is the code that eventually executes __schedule.

NOTE: Even when the waker and the process executing __schedule are the same, the second stack trace might not be a superset of the first. 
This is because between the wakeup and __schedule, the waker may have completed functions that were still pending at the time of the wakeup.

The trace section between the two stack traces shows everything the CPU (where the awakened task will run) does between the moment the task is woken up and the moment it finally starts execution. It uses the function tracer format.

Unfortunately, it is very complex due to a specific occurrence: during the task's scheduling wait, a second interrupt arrives, and it is this second interrupt that leads to the schedule. 
For this reason, the two stack traces at the beginning and end have no relation to each other.

The line showing the arrival of the new interrupt is:
kworker/-130       0dN..1    67us : preempt_schedule_irq <-el1_interrupt


